s of trash come into conflict. Conceptions of waste have shaped forms of reuse and renewal in ancient Mesoamerica, early modern ideas of civility and forced religious conversion in New Spain, and even the modern discipline of archaeology. Newman argues that centuries of assumptions imposed on other places, times, and peoples need to be rethought. This book is not only a broad reconsideration of waste; it is also a call for new forms of archaeology that do not take garbage for granted. Unmaking Waste reveals that waste is not—and never has been—an obvious or universal concept.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of Central AmericaxMaterial culturexHistory. 0aIndians of Central AmericaxSocial life and customs. 0aIndians of MexicoxMaterial culturexHistory. 0aIndians of MexicoxSocial life and customs. 0aIndiansxFirst contact with other peoples. 0aMayasxAntiquities. 0aRefuse and refuse disposalzCentral AmericaxHistory. 0aRefuse and refuse disposalzMexicoxHistory. 0aSocial archaeologyzCentral America. 0aSocial archaeologyzMexico. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aarchaeology, colonialism, Europe, garbage, history, Mesoamerica, reuse, trash, United States.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226826387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document